A complex theorem statement can be decomposed into three parts: preconditions, conclusion, and a traceability anchor. Preconditions are the explicit assumptions and domain restrictions, such as quantified variables, type/class membership, regularity conditions, nondegeneracy assumptions, and any previously established lemmas the theorem depends on. The conclusion is the precise claim proved under those assumptions, usually the equality, inequality, existence, uniqueness, convergence, or structural property asserted by the theorem. A useful way to extract them is to rewrite the theorem in "If [assumptions], then [claim]" form, moving all hypotheses into a numbered assumption list and leaving a single normalized claim. The traceability anchor is a stable identifier linking the theorem to its proof and dependencies, such as a theorem label plus references to definitions, lemmas, and equation numbers used in the statement. In formal work, this can be recorded as: Anchor = {theorem name/ID, source section, dependent definitions, prerequisite lemmas, proof artifact location}. This decomposition improves verification, proof maintenance, and downstream reuse because each assumption, claim, and dependency becomes independently checkable.
